00:01:13.569 --> 00:01:16.569
He cooperated with patients who are Jehovah's Witnesses

00:01:16.569 --> 00:01:19.569
and who, while seeking quality medical and surgical treatment,

00:01:19.569 --> 00:01:22.569
do not accept allogeneic blood transfusion,

00:01:22.569 --> 00:01:27.569
they observe the biblical injunction abstain from blood.

00:01:27.569 --> 00:01:32.569
In 1977, Cooley's team published a report on their 20 years of experience

00:01:32.569 --> 00:01:37.569
with a consecutive series of 542 bloodless cardiovascular surgeries.

00:01:37.569 --> 00:01:41.569
The report noted an acceptably low risk.

00:01:41.569 --> 00:01:45.569
Professor Richard Spence, a pioneer in transfusion alternative strategies.

00:01:45.569 --> 00:01:48.569
The lessons we learned in the early stages of bloodless medicine

00:01:48.569 --> 00:01:51.569
and surgery with the Jehovah's Witness clearly translated

00:01:51.569 --> 00:01:54.569
over all of the rest of our patients.

00:01:54.569 --> 00:01:57.569
So the field now really of blood conservation

00:01:57.569 --> 00:02:00.569
includes the use of multiple alternatives

00:02:00.569 --> 00:02:05.569
and a planned way to avoid the need to transfuse a patient

00:02:05.569 --> 00:02:09.460
with someone else's blood.

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:13.460
We have operated on newborns, we have operated on people in their 90s,

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:17.460
and we use these same techniques and approaches.

00:02:17.460 --> 00:02:22.460
Professor Albert Hu, speaking of efforts in the general patient population.

00:02:22.460 --> 00:02:30.460
In the era when the risks of blood transfusion were not realized as they are today,

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:37.460
15% of all women in such a group of at-risk patients received blood.

00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:41.460
Today, this figure is far below 1%,

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:45.460
even though we are a center for complicated cases.

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:50.460
We've now reduced our transfusion rate

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:55.460
for new replacements, new revision replacements.

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:58.460
I think of the order of 5 to 8%.

00:02:58.460 --> 00:03:01.460
Ideally, we'd like to get it down to zero.

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:04.460
Professor Hetzer points to one reason for such efforts.

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:08.460
Today, at least 80% of the patients

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:13.460
would strongly favor not to have blood transfusions.

00:03:13.460 --> 00:03:15.460
And for legal and ethical reasons,

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:18.460
today attention is increasingly being given

00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:20.460
to inspecting the wishes of the patient.

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:24.460
Experts also cite their desire to avoid medical risks

00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:27.460
