00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:29.460
Any unit that is donated into the blood bank,

00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:32.460
whether it's an allergenic unit or a PAD unit,

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:35.460
there's always the risk of administrative error

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:40.460
and an ABO mismatch and a fatal hemolytic transfusion reaction.

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:45.460
Side effects include not only the transmission of viral diseases

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:50.460
that everybody talks about like HIV or hepatitis B or C,

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:55.460
but also new viruses that are prevalent in the donor population.

00:03:55.460 --> 00:04:00.460
Also, parasitic diseases are more and more transmitted

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:03.460
via blood transfusions.

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:06.460
The public health impact of transfusion in a modulation

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:08.460
is very difficult to estimate.

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:12.460
And we've estimated that approximately in the United States,

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:16.459
we can expect that 10 to 50,000 patients a year

00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:21.459
may be dying from transfusion in a modulation related causes.

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:27.459
Will existing viruses mutate and produce disease?

00:04:27.459 --> 00:04:31.459
There's no reason to believe that they want.

00:04:31.459 --> 00:04:34.459
Many see these risks and the resulting costs,

00:04:34.459 --> 00:04:38.459
but feel that they have no alternatives to allergenic blood.

00:04:38.459 --> 00:04:42.459
However, even the benefits of present policies on the use of allergenic blood

00:04:42.459 --> 00:04:46.459
come under question in view of a groundbreaking study

00:04:46.459 --> 00:04:48.459
by Dr. Paul A. Bear of Canada.

00:04:48.459 --> 00:04:52.459
It compared a liberal transfusion policy with a restrictive one

00:04:52.459 --> 00:04:55.459
in critically ill ICU patients.

00:04:55.459 --> 00:04:59.459
The results were surprising, particularly the mortality rates.

00:04:59.459 --> 00:05:02.459
I talk about the A. Bear paper

00:05:02.459 --> 00:05:04.459
where they showed it more than 800 patients

00:05:04.459 --> 00:05:08.459
that less transfusion results in an improved outcome.

00:05:08.459 --> 00:05:12.459
Other evidence showing the need to review policies on the use of blood

00:05:12.459 --> 00:05:14.459
comes from two earlier studies.

00:05:14.459 --> 00:05:18.459
Consider first the Sanguis study published in 1994.

00:05:18.459 --> 00:05:21.459
Part of a concerted action of the European Commission's

00:05:21.459 --> 00:05:25.459
Medical Research Program, the study analyzed transfusion rates

00:05:25.459 --> 00:05:28.459
in major health care centers across Europe.

00:05:28.459 --> 00:05:31.459
Forty-three teaching hospitals were prospectively studied

00:05:31.459 --> 00:05:34.459
as to their routine transfusion rates

00:05:34.459 --> 00:05:37.459
for six common standardized operations.

00:05:37.459 --> 00:05:40.459
The Sanguis study revealed that different institutions routinely

00:05:40.459 --> 00:05:43.459
transfused drastically different percentages of patients

00:05:43.459 --> 00:05:48.459
for the same surgeries, varying from 0% at some institutions

00:05:48.459 --> 00:05:52.459
to 96% at others on coronary artery bypass graft

00:05:52.459 --> 00:05:57.459
and from 0% to 100% on total hip replacement.

00:05:57.459 --> 00:06:03.459
The main lesson is the variability of a transfusion practice

00:06:03.459 --> 00:06:11.459
from one center to another for the same specific operation.

00:06:11.459 --> 00:06:15.459
In 1998, in Belgium, a follow-up study was published.

00:06:15.459 --> 00:06:20.459
So all types of hospitals were included in the Belgium Biomed Transfusion study

00:06:20.459 --> 00:06:22.459
for surgery.

00:06:22.459 --> 00:06:27.459
And we found exactly the same range of variability.

00:06:27.459 --> 00:06:32.459
So we are left with the conclusion that variability implies

00:06:32.459 --> 00:06:35.459
that a lot of these blood transfusion components

00:06:35.459 --> 00:06:37.459
are being given unnecessarily.

00:06:37.459 --> 00:06:41.459
However, there is a positive note regarding two Belgian hospitals

00:06:41.459 --> 00:06:44.459
that participated in both studies.

00:06:44.459 --> 00:06:48.459
After the Sanguis study, they changed their transfusion policy.

00:06:48.459 --> 00:06:53.459
They had somehow managed to reduce their blood consumption

00:06:53.459 --> 00:06:57.459
for major surgery, like collectomephal cancer,

00:06:57.459 --> 00:07:00.459
by a factor of five, at least.

00:07:00.459 --> 00:07:05.459
The hospitals they was shorter, so we have no evidence

00:07:05.459 --> 00:07:09.459
of increased morbidity, nor mortality.

00:07:09.459 --> 00:07:12.459
In the light of what has been learned in the last few years,

00:07:12.459 --> 00:07:17.459
Professor Philippe Funder-Linden summarizes what many experts have concluded.

00:07:17.459 --> 00:07:22.459
In view of the potential for a better patient care

00:07:22.459 --> 00:07:29.459
and reduced ill-care cost, blood conservation is not an option.

00:07:29.459 --> 00:07:31.459
It's a must.

00:07:31.459 --> 00:07:36.459
But what is the foundation for an effective transfusion alternative program?

00:07:36.459 --> 00:07:39.459
Experts agree that it is a team approach.

00:07:39.459 --> 00:07:46.459
It truly has to be a cooperative effort, a team effort to the approach.

00:07:46.459 --> 00:07:50.459
And it has to be tailored to the patient's condition,

00:07:50.459 --> 00:07:53.459
as well as the operative procedures.

00:07:53.459 --> 00:07:57.459
Some techniques are appropriate for some procedures and some surgeons,

00:07:57.459 --> 00:08:00.459
and not for others.

00:08:00.459 --> 00:08:04.459
The various transfusion alternative techniques used by successful teams

00:08:04.459 --> 00:08:09.459
can be placed under three basic principles or pillars.

00:08:09.459 --> 00:08:15.459
Pre-operative planning involves to realize that a patient has not enough

00:08:15.459 --> 00:08:19.459
anogenous red blood cells for planned operation.

00:08:19.459 --> 00:08:24.459
And this depends not only on the hematocrit,

00:08:24.459 --> 00:08:28.459
but also on the estimated blood volume of a given patient,

00:08:28.459 --> 00:08:33.460
the estimated blood loss that the planned operation is associated with,

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:40.460
and also the transfusion threshold that can be considered reasonable or tolerable

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:42.460
in this individual patient.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:46.460
The first pillar can be defined as appropriate tolerance of anemia.

00:08:46.460 --> 00:08:52.990
This involves reconsidering the standard policy on anemia treatment.

00:08:52.990 --> 00:08:57.990
Some still use a transfusion trigger of a hematocrit of 30%,

00:08:57.990 --> 00:09:01.990
or a hemoglobin level of 10 grams per deciliter for all patients.

00:09:01.990 --> 00:09:07.990
Thresholds that date back to an article by Adams and Lundy published in 1942.

00:09:07.990 --> 00:09:14.990
I am really convinced that there is no place for the magic 10 grams.

00:09:14.990 --> 00:09:19.990
Our experience with Jehovah's Witness has shown that, first of all,

00:09:19.990 --> 00:09:25.990
we don't need the hemoglobin levels we assumed were essential previously.

00:09:25.990 --> 00:09:29.990
But there should be no harder fast rule or there should be no trigger.

00:09:29.990 --> 00:09:34.990
You can anesthetize patients with some procedures depending upon the patient.

00:09:34.990 --> 00:09:38.990
There's always two or three grams if necessary.

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:43.990
All experienced physicians stress the importance of maintaining normal valemia

00:09:43.990 --> 00:09:46.990
via simple volume replacement.

00:09:46.990 --> 00:09:52.990
With adequate volume, oxygen consumption is maintained over a wide range of hemoglobin levels.

00:09:52.990 --> 00:09:57.990
According to Professor Fundalinden, the two main mechanisms responsible

00:09:57.990 --> 00:10:03.990
for the maintenance of adequate tissue oxygenation are an increase in cardiac output.

00:10:04.990 --> 00:10:07.990
And an increase in tissue oxygen extraction.

00:10:07.990 --> 00:10:12.990
In the range of hematocrit values illustrated, the amount of oxygen extracted

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:17.990
from the red blood cells of a non-anemic person is practically the same as that

00:10:17.990 --> 00:10:22.990
taken up from fewer red blood cells under acute normal valemic anemia.

00:10:22.990 --> 00:10:29.990
The first mechanism results from the decreased blood viscosity and sympathetic stimulation.

00:10:29.990 --> 00:10:36.990
The second mechanism results from a redistribution of blood flow to areas of high metabolic demand

00:10:36.990 --> 00:10:42.460
and from improved micro-circulation.

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:48.460
I am really convinced that a better knowledge of the mechanism

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:54.460
allowing the maintenance of adequate tissue oxygenation

00:10:54.460 --> 00:11:01.460
during acute normal valemic anemia could decrease the risk of blood transfusion.

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:05.460
What does experience with this principle alone reveal?

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:08.460
I halved our transfusion rate by simply saying,

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:11.460
could we lower our triggers from 10 to 8?

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:14.460
And just taking a little more control over the decision.

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:17.460
That was very easy. That cost nothing.

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:22.460
We do know that we can allow patients to collaborate

00:11:22.460 --> 00:11:27.460
to relatively low hemoglobin levels without blood transfusions.

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:30.460
Obviously, it is important to plan ahead.

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:35.460
Especially if the patient for religious or other reasons refuses allogeneic blood.

00:11:35.460 --> 00:11:40.460
Preoperative planning requires a careful clinical assessment of the bleeding risks

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:45.460
and a thorough laboratory screening, including standard hematological parameters.

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:49.460
Based on the patient's condition, this may include other tests,

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:55.460
such as a coagulation profile and tests for conditions contributing to anemia.

00:11:55.460 --> 00:11:58.460
Next, there is the need to calculate the safety zone

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:02.460
where tolerable red blood cell loss for a particular patient

00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:04.460
throughout perioperative care.

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:11.460
Here is how Professor Ernst Shaw explains his approach using the example of joint replacement.

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:17.460
All you need is height and weight, male or female, initially hemoglobin, hematocrit.

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:21.460
And you can immediately work out what their blood volume is.

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:24.460
Next, either using your personal data

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:27.460
and anybody who's doing more than a few joint replacements

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:31.460
should be able to go back and look what their typical loss is.

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:35.460
So you want to know what loss there will be for that particular procedure.

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:39.460
The only other thing you need to know is how much can you tolerate?

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:42.460
In other words, how low can you let this patient go?

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:47.460
What if the expected RBC loss is greater than the tolerable?

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:52.460
You can increase the blood loss that is tolerated by the patient

00:12:52.460 --> 00:12:57.460
by simply lowering the threshold of transfusion trigger

00:12:57.460 --> 00:13:06.460
or you can increase the allowable blood loss by increasing the initial hematocrit of the patient

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:14.460
and therefore have the patient start or go into the operation with a higher mass of red blood cells.

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:22.460
Several of these proactive techniques can be grouped under the second pillar, optimizing RBC mass.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:31.460
We can expand the circulating red blood cell mass of the patients before the operation.

00:13:31.460 --> 00:13:40.460
And this can be achieved with cheap hematinics like iron, polycacid, vitamin B12.

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:48.460
For selected cases, recombinant erythropoietin or EPO combined with iron therapy can be used to treat anemia

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:54.460
or to raise the pre-surgical hematocrit to within a range of 45 to 50%.

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:59.460
EPO is normally started 10 to 21 days prior to surgery.

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:09.830
EPO illustrated by small particles increases red cell production by affecting the survival, differentiation,

00:14:09.830 --> 00:14:19.139
and maturation of erythroid cells in the bone marrow.

00:14:19.139 --> 00:14:24.139
In the late erythroblastic stage, the nuclei are expelled.

00:14:24.139 --> 00:14:30.799
Finally, the erythrocytes are pushed into the bloodstream.

00:14:30.799 --> 00:14:38.100
Note the acceleration of red cell production with EPO.

00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:44.100
Besides the increase in RBC mass, under EPO treatment, usually one week is gained.

00:14:44.100 --> 00:14:53.710
Note the comparatively higher hematocrit rise under EPO therapy according to one study.

00:14:53.710 --> 00:15:07.090
And utilizing erythropoietin, we can increase the circulating hemoglobin by one bram decidator for each week of treatment.

00:15:07.090 --> 00:15:14.090
For commenting human erythropoietin therapy is a tool that has also been shown to be effective as a blood conservation strategy.

00:15:14.090 --> 00:15:20.090
It's been shown particularly in orthopedic procedures in patients who are anemic.

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:27.090
And by that I mean whose initial hemoglobin is less than 13 or hematocrit is less than 39%.

00:15:27.090 --> 00:15:31.090
Now we use erythropoietin in very specific cases.

00:15:31.090 --> 00:15:40.090
Like for instance, also the children of Chihuahua's witnesses, where we start to administer this medication four to six weeks before the operation.

